Lab 6: Data Visualisation in R

Question Sheet

Dr Mercedes Torres Torres

Introduction

This question sheet presents a series of exercises designed to make you use R for data visualisation purposes. You will be applying the concepts you learned during the previous labs (data frames, reading data from files, etc.) to analyse and visualise data.

In this lab session, you will learn to:

  • Create simple graphs to analyse your data using basic R.

  • Create sophisticated graphs to analyse data using the ggplot2 library.

  • Choose appropriate visualisation methods for data analysis purposes.

To begin, start your R editor (RStudio or your editor of choice). I recommend that you revise Lecture 4 and Lecture 5 and read the Instruction sheet carefully. Once you have finished reading them, start working on these exercises.

Base R

Use the Iris dataset to create and analyse simple graphs:

  1. Create a pie chart for the Species class in the Iris dataset. Setosa should be blue, versicolor should be yellow and virginica should be magenta. Save this chart as species_piechart.png.
ir = iris
library("ggplot2")
slices <- c(50,50,50)
lbls <- c("Setosa","Versicolor","Virginica")
col <- c("blue","yellow","magenta")
pie(slices, lbls, col = col, main = "Pie chart of Iris Species class")

lbls <- c("Setosa","Versicolor","Virginica")
pie(table(ir$Species), lbls, col = c("blue", "yellow","magenta"))

  1. Create a function called `` that reads the Iris dataset and plots a histogram of petal lengths with:
    1. 30 bars in a colour of your choosing
    2. A sensible title
    3. Two lines of different colour showing the mean and the median
    4. A legend for the median and mean lines
plotPetalLength <- function(){
  ir = iris
  hist(ir$Petal.Length, breaks = seq(1,7,0.5), col = "purple",main = "Histogram of Petal Length")
  abline(v=mean(ir$Petal.Length), col = "orange", lwd = 5)
  abline(v=median(ir$Petal.Length), col = "blue", lwd = 5)
  legend("topright", c("mean", "median"), col = c("orange", "blue"), pch = 16)
}
plotPetalLength()

  1. Create a dotplot that groups samples into their species and shows how the petal lengths of all instances vary. Each group should have a different colour of your choosing.
x = ir[order(ir$Petal.Length),]
x$cls = factor(x$Species)
x$color[x$cls=='setosa'] = 'red'
x$color[x$cls=='virginica'] = 'blue'

dotchart(x$Petal.Length, labels = row.names(x), cex=.7, groups = x$cls,
         main = "Petal Length \n grouped by Plant type",
         xlab = "length in cms", gcolor = "black", color = x$color)

Advanced Visualisation

In this section, we will be using ggplot2 to create more complicated and informative graphs in R. In terms of data, we will be using a dataset of footballers from different regions in Narnia. This dataset is called team and you can download it from Moodle. Remember that all graphs need to be titled and all axes labelled.

  1. Create a histogram of that shows the age distribution from all players at intervals of 1 year.

    1. What is the most common age? How common is it?

  2. Create a histogram that shows the salary distribution of players that are Defenders. Choose a sensible interval.

  3. Repeat the histogram of task 1, but grouping the data according to Gender.

    1. How many women are aged 27?
    2. How many men are aged 33?

  4. Create a histogram that shows the age distribution of Forward players grouped into teams. Choose a sensible age interval.

library("ggplot2")
ggplot(team, aes(x = Age, fill = Team)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Years", breaks = seq(min(team$Age),max(team$Age),2)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Frecuency") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Age by Team") + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Spectral")

Choosing the right visualisation techniques

In this section, you will have to use the skills developed in the previous labs and use statistics and visualisation to provide a meaningful analysis of the Reviews dataset. You can download the reviews.csv dataset from Moodle.

The Reviews dataset contains over 84,500 instances of people rating different movies. The attributes included in the dataset are:

  • userID: the ID of the reviewer. One reviewer can have a variable number of reviews.
  • movieID: the movie reviewed by the reviewer.
  • rating: how many stars the reviewer has given to the movie. The lowest score is 0.0 and the highest is 5.0.
  • date: date and time in which the review was uploaded.
  • movieTitle: the title of the movie reviewed.
  • movieYear: the year the movie was released.
  • movieGenre: the genre of the move. Although one movie can be of many different genres, for the purpose of this exercise, we will only consider the main genre of a movie.

You have been hired by Calabaza Productions, a production company interested in studying trends in reviews from movies released in the last hundred years. Your job is to provide a comprehensive set of statistics and visualisations that can help Calabaza Productions understand the dataset.

  1. Analyse the data to familiarise yourself with the contents of the dataset. Calculate appropriate centrality and dispersion measurements for all attributes.

  2. Use analytics to answer the following questions:

    1. How many reviewers have participated?
    2. How many movies have been reviewed?
    3. Which reviewer has the most reviews? And the least?
    4. Which genre has the most reviews? And the least?
    5. Which is the oldest movie reviewed? Who reviewed it (if more than one reviewer rated it, return all of them)?
    6. Which one(s) is (are) the highest-rated genres of the 1990s?
    7. What is the most reviewed movie? What is its average score?

  3. Use visualisation to answer the following questions:

    1. What is the distribution of ratings for all movie genres?
